  "text": "The OpenJDK security provider registration framework is implemented across the following files in sg-evals/jdk--742e735d:\n\n1. **Base Provider class** (`src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Provider.java`): The `java.security.Provider` base class defines the `putService(Service s)` method (line 1221) that all providers use to register cryptographic algorithm implementations.\n\n2. **SunJCE provider** (`src/java.base/share/classes/com/sun/crypto/provider/SunJCE.java`): The `SunJCE` class extends `Provider` and registers JCE (Java Cryptography Extension) algorithms including ciphers (AES, DES, RSA), key generators, MACs (HmacSHA*), and key agreement protocols.\n\n3. **SunJSSE provider** (`src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/ssl/SunJSSE.java`): The `SunJSSE` class extends `java.security.Provider` and registers SSL/TLS-related services including SSLContext, TrustManagerFactory, KeyManagerFactory, and KeyStore factories.\n\n4. **SunEC provider** (`src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/ec/SunEC.java`): The `SunEC` class extends `Provider` and registers elliptic curve algorithm implementations including ECDSA signatures (SHA*withECDSA, SHA3-*withECDSAinP1363Format), ECDH key agreement, and EC key pair generation.\n\n5. **Sun provider** (`src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/provider/Sun.java`): The `Sun` class extends `Provider` and registers core/foundational algorithms like SHA message digests, DSA signatures, SecureRandom implementations, and certificate factories.\n\n6. **ProviderConfig** (`src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/jca/ProviderConfig.java`): The `ProviderConfig` class implements the lazy-loading mechanism for security providers. It maps provider names to their implementing classes and defers actual class loading until a provider is first requested. It uses an inner `ProviderLoader` class backed by `ServiceLoader<Provider>` for discovering providers."
}

